					<div class="content-intro-text">
						<h1>Science, technology and innovation in ACP agricultural and rural development</h1>
													<p class="author"><strong>Author:</strong>
								Judith A. Francis</p>
																								
													<p class="date"><strong>Date:</strong>
							07/01/2005</p>
																									<p class="intro">Introduction:</p>
							 








 




  
  

	
	<a href="/var/knowledge/storage/images-versioned/19532/1-eng-GB/3rd_meeting_of_cta_s_advisory_committee_on_st_for_acp_agriculture1.jpg" rel="lightbox[]" >	
	  </a>
	
		
			
	
  	






	 
  





	<p>Science and technology have long been recognized as the catalysts for industrialization and, when linked with innovation, as the key to achieving social and economic development and global competitiveness. However, while developed countries continue to invest pproximately 3% of GDP in enhancing their scientific and technological capabilities, investments in research and development in developing countries, whether from public, private or international sources, are estimated at less than 1% of GDP. New strategies focusing on science, technology and innovation (ST&amp;I) and the adoption of both 'traditional' and 'modern' approaches to creating, sharing and building knowledge systems, are needed to help developing countries improve their national and regional ST&amp;I systems and revitalize their economies.</p>
						
						
						
						<br/>&nbsp;
					</div> 
					<br class="cl">
				</div> 
				 
			
				<div id="content-item">
											<div class="box-content">
							<a class="storylist" href="/en/layout/set/print/content/view/full/1336">Print</a>
																						| <a href="#comment">Comments</a>
													</div> 
						<br class="cl">
		
					 
	
				</div> 
			
				<div id="main-content" class="content view">					

	                          
			

	<!-- BEGIN BODY TEXT -->	
	
			<div class="stdtext">	
			
 <p>
The agricultural sector is the foundation of the economies of many African, Caribbean and Pacific (ACP) countries. Consequently, any programme that seeks to encourage greater emphasis on ST&amp;I must address issues related to the application of ST&amp;I in the transformation of their agricultural sectors. ACP countries need to be supported in their efforts to compete in national, regional and global markets, and to refocus their efforts to increase investments in S&amp;T and build strong national and regional innovation systems<br />for their economic and social development. In September 2003, CTA's Science and Technology Strategies programme initiated a process to promote and facilitate the ACP dialogue to improve ST&amp;I policy formulation and implementation and to strengthen their ST&amp;I systems. The programme has three components: </p> <p><b>Supporting and facilitating the policy dialogue on ST&amp;I</b> </p> <p>
This component aims to support dialogue at national and regional levels, and between the ACP and the EU. In 2003, for example, CTA convened the second meeting of the ACP Informal Working Group on S&amp;T, which led to its formalization as the Advisory Committee on S&amp;T for ACP Agricultural and Rural Development. In 2004 CTA facilitated three regional meetings on ?Enhancing the S&amp;T Policy Dialogue ? Innovation for Development?, which brought together policymakers, scientists, education specialists, engineers, information and communication experts, representativesof farmers? and women?s groups and other non-governmental organizations, the private sector and youth. The participants discussed national, regional and international ST&amp;I policies, strategies and programmes, assessed the experiences of other regions, and made recommendations for improving the ST&amp;I<br />
policy dialogue. A key outcome of all three meetings was the recognition that greater emphasis and resources must be made available to improve science education, and specifically tertiary education in agriculture, if the ACP regions are to produce the<br />highly trained and skilled professionals and researchers that are required to transform ACP agriculture. The third meeting of the Advisory Committee will take place in Wageningen, the Netherlands, on 23-26 November 2004. </p> <p><b>Information management</b> </p> <p>This component aims to facilitate access to and exchanges of information, experiences and technologies. CTA?s newest web portal, Knowledge for Development, is intended to raise awareness of national, regional and international developments in ST&amp;I and their implications for ACP agricultural and rural development, and to support the ST&amp;I policy dialogue. The website provides opinions from ACP and EU experts and other stakeholders, relevant documents and links to related web resources, and facilitates networking among ACP and international institutions.</p> <p><b>Knowledge development</b> </p> <p>This component emphasizes building national and regional capacities for effective participation in the ST&amp;I policy process, developing national ST&amp;I systems, and strengthening negotiation and lobbying skills. The focus is on strengthening local and indigenous knowledge systems that can enhance the quality and effectiveness of the ST&amp;I infrastructure and its contribution to economic transformation. CTA is also working to ensure that civil society, especially farmers, are not excluded from the process. Farmers have an enormous capacity for innovation, driven by the need for economic survival, and their innovations have an integral role to play in agricultural research and development. If properly harnessed, their innovations could contribute to the future development and transformation of ACP agriculture throughout the entire production, processing and marketing chain. By involving and mobilizing civil society, and encouraging collaboration between farmers, the scientific community and policy makers, CTA hopes to reduce the mystique that surrounds ST&amp;I, and ensure that all stakeholders participate in and contribute to the development of strong national and regional ST&amp;I systems.</p> <p>In a knowledge-based society, science, technology and innovation are not only the domain of the well educated, but are the expression of a strong, dynamic and evolving ST&amp;I system that values the inputs and contributions of all stakeholders. Facilitating the flow of information and knowledge for the benefit of all actors, and using every available means of communication to build, strengthen and expand the knowledge network are critical to the success of CTA?s ST&amp;I initiative. The S&amp;T Strategies programme respects the capacity and capability of all its partners and collaborators at national, regional and international levels, and will continue to support their efforts to re-engineer and strengthen their ST&amp;I systems.</p> <p>Readers are encouraged to provide inputs and participate in the process of knowledge development and sharing and in the policy dialogues. </p> <p><i>Judith A. Francis is Senior Programme Coordinator, S&amp;T Strategies, CTA, Wageningen</i> </p>
		</div>
		
	<!-- END BODY TEXT -->
		
			
		
	
	
			
				

		<strong class="date_small">07/01/2005</strong>
